  "prompt": "Why is April Fools' Day Poisson d'avril in French?",
  "response": "In French, April Fools' Day is called \"Poisson d'avril,\" which literally translates to \"April Fish.\" The origin of this tradition dates back to the 16th century in France. According to folklore, people would stick paper fish on each other's backs as a joke. When the victim discovered the fish, people would laugh and shout \"Poisson d'avril!\" \n\nThere are several theories about why fish are associated with this day:\n\n1. Some believe it relates to the zodiac sign Pisces, which falls during this time of year.\n\n2. Others suggest it might be connected to the abundance of easy-to-catch fish in French rivers during early spring.\n\n3. Another theory links it to the end of Lent, when fish was traditionally eaten, and the changing of the calendar from the Julian to the Gregorian system.\n\nRegardless of the exact origin, the tradition of drawing or cutting out paper fish and secretly attaching them to people's backs continues in France and other French-speaking countries as part of the April Fools' Day celebrations.",
